title.narrative: Media for Transparent and Accountable Governance (M-TAG)

description.narrative: (Georgia): M-TAG works with competitively selected group of 14 media organizations throughout Georgia to concurrently increase their capacity in content production, web publishing, and business operations. M-TAG works with media partners to provide fact-based reporting and analysis, thus helping the audience to discern disinformation and propaganda and combat anti-Western sentiment M-TAG supports raising reporting standards across the journalism profession by providing operational funds to Ethics Charter and Multimedia Education Center (MEC), to acquire industry-relevant and hands-on production skills. M-TAG helps media partners keep ethnic minority communities and communities affected by conflict on both sides of Administrative Boundary Line informed and provides them with platforms for expression and exchange of ideas and information.With FY 2019 Funds the program will support regional outlets to disseminate COVID-19 related critical pandemic, social or political information in a timely manner. M-TAG will support regional media outlets, including those covering minority communities with language appropriate content, through content production grants and technical assistance to ensure information about continued vigilance, re-emergence and response and recovery efforts and opportunities is well communicated to Georgia's citizens. M-TAG will also support media outlets to analyze and report of COVID-19 response and recovery efforts and communicate citizen's concerns to decision makers at the local and central levels. M-TAG will continue to assist media outlets to improve their online presence, including website development, multimedia content production, online advertising, analytics, editorial management, and management of online TV studios. In addition, the program will continue to support the Georgian Charter of Journalistic Ethics and the Multimedia Education Center, two key institutions that promote high standards in Georgia's media sector.. .

title.narrative: Advancing CSO Capacities and Engaging Society for Sustainability (ACCESS)

description.narrative: (Georgia): .USAID's Advancing Civil Society Capacities and Engaging Society for Sustainability (ACCESS) activity works to increase citizen engagement with Georgian civil society organizations (CSOs) from across the democratic spectrum. The activity, improves organizational and technical capacity of CSOs to monitor and influence government policies and processes in a non-partisan manner. ACCESS achieves these outcomes through a combination of small grants, trainings, and technical assistance to local organizations; and by supporting the Network of Centers for Civic Engagement in 10 cities, which operate as politically neutral gathering spaces for public discourse on issues of relevant to the Georgian public. By enabling a more constituent-connected, organizationally mature cadre of CSOs, activities assist CSOs to become legitimate representatives of citizens' concerns.With FY 2019 funds ACCESS will expand COVID-19-related programming to address medium and longer-term implications of the pandemic. ACCESS will work with local organizations to continue to build communities' trust in civil society, demonstrate efficient use of resources and encourage community investment in COVID-19 related activities through volunteerism and community resource mobilization. The activity builds the capacity of the civil society sector to contribute to more transparent and accountable governance (ICS MO 1.1) by facilitating dialogue between citizens and their government about key priorities. This activity aligns with U.S. national security interests and supports the U.S. policy priority of promoting American leadership through balanced engagement and increased partnerships with civil society (JSP 3.3 and JRS 4.1). The activity works to counter Russian soft power that discredits civil society. It mitigates democratic backsliding by ensuring an active citizenry and supports the U.S. goals to advance Georgia's Euro-Atlantic integration... .. .. .

title.narrative: The Zrda Activity in Georgia (Zrda)

description.narrative: (Georgia): Russian occupation of Abkhazia and South Ossetia, borderization along these regions, and discontent in communities with ethnically or religiously marginalized populations are direct threats to Georgia's economic and political stability. By building economic resilience in communities along the administrative boundary line (ABL) and regions with marginalized populations, the Zrda program directly counters malign Kremlin influence, contributes to ongoing economic activity along the ABL, and supports Georgia to restore its territorial integrity...Zrda will build the economic resilience of more than 80 communities by supporting at least 800 micro-, small- and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs) to acquire equipment and certifications to increase productive capacity and meet international quality standards for goods and services. Zrda will also support the GOG agencies to promote new technologies and innovation; strengthen the public and private sector extension systems; extend digital marketing and electronic matchmaking services between buyers, producers, and service providers; and develop public-private partnerships to build economic opportunities in targeted communities. In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Zrda will support Georgia's hospitality businesses across 17 municipalities to implement required sanitary regulations...Zrda will provide $1.3 million in training, grants, and technical assistance to advance USAID/Georgia's CDCS DO1: Resilience to external malign influence strengthened (CAATSA Goal 8) and DO3: Inclusive high-value employment opportunities through increased economic growth. By co-investing with the private sector and the GOG to incentivize new business development along the ABL (JRS 2.3.1), Zrda ensures effectiveness to the American taxpayer (JSP 4), promotes American leadership through balanced engagement (JSP 3.3), and mobilizes additional resources to advance Georgia's self-reliance (JRS 5.2.1)... .. .

description.narrative: (Georgia): .Good Governance Initiative (GGI) is designed to support the GOG in strengthening transparency, accountability, and effectiveness of select governance and service delivery systems to achieve: improved administrative and financial management of public institutions; improved access to independent, reliable and balanced information on government performance; strengthened policy development and lawmaking; and strengthened institutional oversight of GOG. GGI's government counterparts include the Prime Minister's Office; the Ministries of Finance, Health, Justice, and Regional Development; Parliament; the State Audit Office; Public Defender's and State Inspector's Offices and select local governments. Interventions will work with government and civil society representatives to enhance public participation, public awareness and monitoring of public administration and parliamentary strengthening reforms. The activity will have emphasis on COVID19 response. ..Using FY 2019 funds, GGI's activities will be focused on:.Supporting the GoG in COVID19 response through policy research in the governance areas impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic; analysis of government operations during the pandemic; mapping of public services and developing recommendations for operationalizing essential public services to be accessible remotely; developing guidelines for the operation of civil service during the crisis; supporting remote operations of the Parliament; etc. Supporting the implementation of the Local Government Decentralization Strategy (2020-2025) by providing necessary technical assistance in select areas.Supporting the implementation of Anti-Corruption Action Plan (2019-2020) and Open Government Partnership Action Plans in select municipalities.Improving state oversight through supporting the Parliament and the State Audit Office as well as building internal control functions of the government agencies... .

title.narrative: HealthLink: Accelerating Ukraine's Efforts to End HIV Activity

description.narrative: The HealthLink Project, Accelerating Ukraines Efforts to End HIV, has started in October 2017. All efforts of the project are focused on accelerating the process of overcoming the HIV epidemic in Ukraine due to an opportunity of testing for HIV quickly and securely and starting the treatment as soon as possible. The project is being implemented by the Alliance for Public Health, in partnership with the All-Ukrainian Network of PLWH, funded by the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID). The goal of the project is to improve access of people living with HIV and people at high risk of infection to high-quality services for the infection prevention and treatment and high-quality medical and social support, as well as reduction of stigma and discrimination of people living with HIV from the side of medical workers. In translation from English, the name of the project literally means link (connection) to health.

title.narrative: Cultivating Media Independence (CMI) Initiative Activity in the Kyrgyz Republic, Media-K

description.narrative: (Kyrgyz Republic): USAID's Media-K initiative will continue to support the development of a more professional, financially viable, and independent media sector. This activity will result in media outlets which better serve the public interest by providing access to diverse and balanced information and analyses about the issues that are of most concern to citizens, while providing a counterweight to state-funded media. This activity will include the provision of training, technical expertise, and mentoring to Kyrgyzstani journalists, media outlets, and production companies to help them build their skills and increase the production of high-quality domestic content. The activity will stimulate the production of domestic content that responds to audience demand, strengthen the ability of targeted media outlets to use audience research to attract more advertising, and bring together disparate stakeholders to advocate for a healthy enabling environment for media businesses. This activity supports ICS objective 3.1: Support a more inclusive and accountable democracy.

Objectives for Kyrgyz Republic: Media-K aims to strengthen the professionalism and independence of media in the Kyrgyz Republic in order to ensure that citizens of the Kyrgyz Republic have greater access to diverse and balanced information, are less vulnerable to media bias, and are empowered to make better-informed civic decisions that reflect their communities’ priorities to best serve the public interest.

title.narrative: Suaahara II (Integrated Nutrition Program II)

description.narrative: (Nepal): .Suahaara II focuses on the 1,000-day period between conception and a child's second birthday as a critical window to shape a child's cognitive and physical development through improved nutrition. With FY 2020 funds, the activity will continue to reduce the prevalence of stunting, underweight, and wasting among children; improve household health, nutrition and water, sanitation and hygiene behaviors and practices; increase the use of quality health services; increase the consumption of diverse and nutritious foods by women and their families; and support counseling and behavior change communication on family planning at mothers' groups. Suaahara II will work with the GON in 389 municipalities using evidence-based, multi-sectoral nutrition interventions at the policy, community, and household levels. Suaahara II will improve health and nutrition behaviors and reduce the impact of health emergencies such as COVID-19 on nutrition by strengthening community health systems. This will include training health facility staff on the promotion of exclusive breastfeeding, infant and young child feeding, maternal and newborn care, integrated management of acute malnutrition, integrated management of childhood illness, and maternal and adolescent nutrition. In addition, it will promote essential hygiene actions such as safe drinking water and disposal of feces, healthy timing and spacing for pregnancy, and will provide information on a wide range of voluntary family planning methods and information on service availability. ..Helen Keller International has vast experience implementing integrated nutrition interventions, which contribute to Nepal's self-reliance. Improving nutritional health ensures a healthy and productive workforce in support of Embassy Kathmandu's ICS Goal Two: Increase America's prosperity by developing Nepal as a reliable economic partner, and MO 2.2, Nepal improves health and education outcomes to increase economic productivity....

Objectives for Nepal: Promote key Maternal, Infant and Young Child Nutrition (MIYCN) practices through an intensivebehavior change strategy, including interpersonal communication activities, radio programs, and theuse of mobile technology at the community level. Expand coverage of the community-based integrated management of newborn and childhood illnessprogram and strengthen growth monitoring and promotion at outreach clinics and health facilities. Enhance clean water, sanitation, and hygiene conditions of household facilities and establish privatesector linkages to promote WASH technologies. Improve consumption of nutritious food through increased production, improved post-harveststorage, and processing diverse nutritious food, especially for women farmers from disadvantagedgroups. Strengthen coordination on health and nutrition between government and other stakeholdersthrough the Food Security and Nutrition Coordination Committee, Nepal Nutrition Group,Nutrition Technical Committee, Safe Motherhood sub- committee, Family Planning Sub -committee,and Reproductive Health Coordination Committee. Strengthen the technical, managerial, operational capacity of health and non-health sectorstakeholders at the district and Village Development Committee (VDC) levels to enhance MSNPimplementation.

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): .The Rice and Diversified Crops activity will partner with private sector firms and other stakeholders to improve rice productivity by smallholder farmers, as well as enable them to acquire the skills and knowledge for enhanced rotational crops that will strengthen market competitiveness in the agriculture sector by improving value chain efficiencies, access to finance, and post-harvest services. To contribute to reducing the impact of COVID-19, the activity will strengthen or re-establish local markets by investing in key value chains; support mechanization and labor saving methods, due to potential labor shortages; identify other opportunities to increase the financial resilience of small and medium enterprises; and leverage existing information dissemination programs (e.g., extension and digital tools) to share critical COVID-19 messages...This activity will support the Global Food Security Strategy and significantly contribute to achieving the State-USAID Joint Strategic Plan Goal Two, the Indo-Pacific Strategy through private sector engagement, and U.S. government's mission objective of improved food security in Bangladesh

title.narrative: Social and Behavior Change Communication Activity (Ujjiban)

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): The Ujjiban Social and Behavior Change Communication (SBCC) activity will generate demand for and increase the use of high-quality services for maternal, neonatal, child and adolescent health; family planning; nutrition and tuberculosis, and improve adoption of healthy behaviors in selected districts under in both Sylhet and Chattrogram divisions. At the national level, Ujjiban will strengthen the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare's capacity and systems, to effectively design, develop, coordinate and implement SBCC interventions. With FY 2020 funds, Ujjiban will intensify its focus on gender and health by using diverse communication media and methods (both traditional and new) as well as community outreach programs to encourage audience members to adopt key health behaviors in the areas of maternal, neonatal and child health; family planning, tuberculosis, and nutrition. Ujjiban will also carry out campaigns to raise awareness on ending early marriage and combating gender-based violence. The activity will further explore opportunities to leverage the private sector to ensure greater coverage of Ujjiban's SBCC products. To address risk communication and community engagement on COVID-19, USAID, through the Ujjiban activity, will strengthen risk communication systems, improve public communication, support community engagement, and address misperceptions and misinformation.This activity will support the U.S. National Security Strategy Pillar IV, the State-USAID Joint Strategic Plan Goal Two, and the U.S. government's mission objective of improved health status in Bangladesh..

title.narrative: FTF Bangladesh USAID’s Leaving No One Behind Activity

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): Mission Aviation Fellowship (MAF) flight will continue supporting USAID and its partner agencies to access hard-to-reach areas in Bangladesh to ensure that when development goals are achieved, they are achieved for everyone. Through chartered and shuttle flights, MAF will continue and broaden its flight services to all development and humanitarian agencies working to save human life and improve the livelihoods of vulnerable people in Bangladesh. MAF flight services will help increase the chances of aid agencies accessing hard-to-reach-areas towards ensuring that no one was left behind. This activity enables improved access to remote and marginalized areas, which is necessary for effective activity oversight and accountability. This activity was selected as the most cost effective way to provide activity oversight in remote areas for humanitarian assistance. MAF will contribute to activity monitoring oversight, needs assessment, joint missions with other development partners and private sector organizations in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, Rohingya and host communities, as well as the areas focused on health, education, and population. The service will be used where the commercial vehicles are not feasible and less accessible. In addition MAF service may contribute to emergency services for medical supply for COVID test kits, lab reagents and TOT for service providers in remote public health facilities. title.narrative: Chittagong Hill Tracts Watershed Co-Management Activity (CHTWCA)

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): CHTWCA builds regional resilience by reducing threats to ecosystems and wildlife through improved governance of natural resources. Its biodiversity objective is to reduce threats through an integrated ecosystem management approach that conserves the natural habitats of Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) watershed through environmental governance mechanisms. With FY 2020 funds, CHTWCA will provide direct technical assistance to the Forest Department, Ministry of CHT Affairs, Hill District Councils, Village Common Forest Management Committees and forest dependent communities to strengthen gender responsive local resilience by sustaining capacity to protect and manage the natural ecosystems of the CHT. This approach will improve the management of community and government managed forests that contributes to an integrated ecosystem management process. It will focus on finalizing an integrated watershed management plan for Reserved Forests. It will provide training on sustainable forest management, market linked resilient livelihoods and livelihood diversification. During COVID-19, UNDP will help communities to continue resilient livelihoods with market and private sector linkages. It will also raise awareness against poaching and illegal logging to ensure these activities do not increase during this period.UNDP is one of the few actors active in CHT, and has an unique comparative advantage due to its long experience, technical expertise, and established working relationships with local and government stakeholders. A community-based approach including co-management in the protected areas is the best approach through CHTWCA because it brings a diverse set of community members together for decisions to protect forest areas for water security.CHTWCA aligns with U.S. National Security Objectives of countering illegal trafficking in drugs, persons, and wildlife, and supports the U.S. government's objective of strengthening resilience to natural hazards..

title.narrative: USAID Inform Asia Associate Award #2 - Technical assistance to strengthen malaria surveillance and the use of strategic information for malaria programming

description.narrative: (USAID Regional Development Mission-Asia (RDM/A)): .This activity provides technical assistance to the Thai national malaria program to: 1) strengthen malaria surveillance systems for the detection, notification, and response to malaria cases; 2) evaluate malaria elimination approaches and strategies for implementation and scale-up; and 3) generate and use strategic information (including data from anti-malarial drug therapeutic efficacy monitoring and documentation write-ups). Technical assistance provided through Inform Asia will result in the development of key strategic information products used by various key stakeholders, such as a user-friendly malaria information system, dashboards to facilitate analysis and decision-making, technical assessments, advocacy briefs, and relevant publications. USAID expects that by the end of this award, Thailand's national malaria program will have increased technical capacity to use strategic information to plan, budget, implement, and monitor data-driven, technically sound, and cost-effective malaria programming that maximizes disease impact-a cornerstone in the road to a malaria-free Thailand by 2024. Strengthening malaria elimination is within the interest of global and US national security since it helps to create a more stable and prosperous region that advances American security and economic interests. Furthermore, successful health programs are a key component to ensuring and enhancing prosperity and good governance. For FY 2020, the activity will focus on the dashboard and visualization of the drug resistance monitoring data system, or iDES, integration of new essential data sets, providing online training on surveillance for elimination efforts adapted to COVID-19, providing M&E and data analysis for malaria elimination, and building government staff capacity on MIS data use for research and malaria elimination studies. .. .
